description:
*** Warning ***
Intense strobe lights from 9:46 to 10:04

This video is very similar in concept to what I did with the PlayStation 2 BIOS corruption video, but this time it's for the original PlayStation console. Unlike other corruptions you can find on YouTube, I also showcase memory card manager and CD player corruptions.

I used Vinesauce ROM Corruptor to corrupt the BIOS files, ePSXe and XEBRA for emulating the PS1 (XEBRA allowed me to insert the game disc, while in CD player, which is why I used it sometimes), and a handful of custom scripts to test these corruptions.

comments.text: How do you do ps1 bios corruptions? I can do ps1 game corruptions, just not the bios.
comments.author: @GameBreaker50

comments.text:
Basically I used a couple of quick and dirty batch files, which allowed me to drag and drop the BIOS files into the .bat files, which then launched either ePSXe or Xebra emulator depending on what I wanted to showcase (ePSXe was easier to setup, but Xebra allowed me to play audio CDs and stuff like that).

Many people might not realize this, but ePSXe.exe actually supports several command line arguments, which allow you to directly boot into the BIOS or even load the BIOS without a game disc inserted.

Here are some examples of argument switches you can use (either use command prompt or make a shortcut and append these switches to the end of the destination field):

To load the bios and show the PlayStation logo:
<FULL PATH TO ePSXe.EXE> -slowboot -bios <FULL PATH TO BIOS FILE> -nogui -loadbin <FULL PATH TO A PS1 GAME ISO>

To load the bios without a disc:
<FULL PATH TO ePSXe.EXE> -slowboot -bios <FULL PATH TO BIOS FILE>

To load the bios and show the forbidden image error screen:
<FULL PATH TO ePSXe.EXE> -slowboot -bios <FULL PATH TO BIOS FILE> -nogui

To load the bios in the Xebra emulator:
<FULL PATH TO XEBRA.EXE> -OSROM <FULL PATH TO BIOS FILE> -RUN1

If there are any spaces in any of the paths, surround them with quotes (example: "C:\long random path\ePSXe.exe")

To stop ePSXe, in case it stops responding (press Windows+R and then run this):
taskkill /F /IM epsxe.exe


Here are the contents of all the batch files I used:
::kill_epsxe.bat
taskkill /F /IM epsxe.exe

::run_bios.bat
@start D:\Romid\PS1\epsxe.exe -slowboot -bios "%1" -nogui -loadbin "D:\Romid\PS1\isos\PLAYSTATION.CUE"

::run_bios_forbidden_image.bat
@start D:\Romid\PS1\epsxe.exe -slowboot -bios "%1" -nogui

::run_bios_nodisc.bat
@start D:\Romid\PS1\epsxe.exe -slowboot -bios "%1"

::run_bios_xebra.bat
@start "" "D:\Dokumendid ja muud failid\Tarkvara\Mngud\xebra\XEBRA.EXE" -OSROM "%1" -RUN1
